A RESOLUTION
To urge and request the surgeon general and the Louisiana Department of Health to conduct
a professional assessment of fenbendazole or similar potential treatments for cancer
or other medical conditions, to evaluate state-level options for supporting further
review, and to develop guidance on engaging the United States Food and Drug
Administration for compassionate use, expanded access programs, or prioritized
clinical trials, while maintaining rigorous patient safety and evidence-based
standards.
WHEREAS, there is growing public interest in fenbendazole, a veterinary
anthelmintic drug, due to an increasing number of anecdotal reports and patient testimonials
from across the United States, including Louisiana, describing significant recoveries or
remissions from various types of cancer after self-administration, often in conjunction with
other therapies; and
WHEREAS, preclinical studies have indicated that fenbendazole may possess
anti-tumor properties, such as disrupting microtubules in cancer cells and inhibiting tumor
growth in laboratory models; and
WHEREAS, despite these preliminary findings, fenbendazole is not currently
approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration for human use, and clinical
evidence in humans remains limited to case reports and observational data without
large-scale randomized controlled trials; and
WHEREAS, organizations such as the American Cancer Society have cautioned
against the off-label use of fenbendazole outside of controlled clinical settings due to
potential risks, including liver inflammation, and unknown drug interactions; and
WHEREAS, the experiences of the COVID-19 pandemic have highlighted the value
of considering innovative and nontraditional treatment options during times of urgent
